President Barack Obama has announced his intention to nominate Gayle E. Smith as Administrator of the U.S. Agency for International Development (USAID). Smith has been a senior leader on international development, humanitarian crisis response, and democracy issues on the National Security Council staff for the past six years. She has played a key role in guiding America's international development policy, responding to humanitarian crises worldwide, and ensuring that development remains a priority in the national security agenda. Smith has also been involved in the creation of Presidential initiatives such as Feed the Future, Power Africa, the Global Health Security Agenda, and the Open Government Partnership. Prior to her current position, she was a Senior Fellow at the Center for American Progress and held various roles in the National Security Council and the U.S. Agency for International Development. Smith has extensive experience in Africa as a journalist and working for non-governmental relief and development organizations. She holds a B.A. from the University of Colorado at Boulder.